    <node id="The Delaware chief, Chingachgook, approached the palisades with caution, keeping his eyes on the loops of the building, expecting to see a rifle muzzle or hear a sharp crack. He succeeded in reaching the piles in safety, using the heads of the palisades as protection between him and the hut. This reduced the chances of any attempt on his life while covered. Chingachgook carefully examined every object that might betray enemies or violence, but he found no signs.&#10;&#10;After throwing the &quot;ominosus article&quot; (a moccasin) into the canoe, Chingachgook prepared to depart. He knew retreat was dangerous, as the enemy could now understand his motive for reconnoitering. However, he chose to retire with an air of confidence, attempting to dispel any suspicion.&#10;&#10;When considering Hist's proposal to retrieve the moccasin from the palisade, Chingachgook declined, arguing that it was a warrior's task. He refused to let his betrothed proceed and instead took on the responsibility himself." />
