    <node id="The dispute between Hutter and Chingachgook is about whether there are signs of a Huron near the old hut. Chingachgook believes that he can see signs of a Huron's presence, while Hutter disagrees and thinks that Chingachgook has the wrong end of the glass.&#10;&#10;Chingachgook's belief is based on his experience and knowledge as an Indian, suggesting that he has better eyesight and understanding of Huron tactics than Hutter. On the other hand, Hutter thinks that a white man's senses are superior to an Indian's when truly tested. Therefore, he dismisses Chingachgook's claim and assumes that there are no signs of a Huron near the old hut.&#10;&#10;Later in the narrative, it is revealed that Chingachgook was right all along. He finds a moccasin floating against the pile of the castle, indicating the possibility of enemy presence. Hutter then acknowledges that the moccasin might have drifted from a distance or fallen from the foot of some scout, suggesting that it could be a sign of Huron's presence near the old hut. However, at this point in the narrative, Hutter still thinks that Chingachgook has the wrong end of the glass, indicating their differing opinions and beliefs." />
