    <node id=" soon in rapid motion. Still, neither party resorted to their&#10;greatest exertions from the outset, both knowing that the chase&#10;was likely to be arduous and long. Like two vessels of war that are&#10;preparing for an encounter, they seemed desirous of first ascertaining&#10;their respective rates of speed, in order that they might know how to&#10;graduate their exertions, previously to the great effort. A few minutes&#10;sufficed to show the Hurons that the girls were expert, and that it&#10;would require all their skill and energies to overtake them.&#10;&#10;Judith had inclined towards the eastern shore at the commencement of the&#10;chase, with a vague determination of landing and flying to the woods as&#10;a last resort, but as she approached the land, the certainty that scouts&#10;must be watching her movements made her reluctance to adopt such an&#10;expedient unconquerable. Then she was still fresh, and had sanguine&#10;hopes of being able to tire out her pursuers. With such feelings she&#10;gave a sweep with her paddle, and sheered off from the fringe of dark&#10;hemlocks beneath the shades of which she was so near entering, and held&#10;her way again, more towards" />
    <node id="&#10;scow. This demonstration produced no other effect than to keep the Ark&#10;nearer to the scene of action, and to enable those in her to become&#10;witnesses of the chase. The canoe of Judith was about a quarter of a&#10;mile south of that of the Hurons, a little nearer to the east shore, and&#10;about the same distance to the southward of the castle as it was from&#10;the hostile canoe, a circumstance which necessarily put the last nearly&#10;abreast of Hutter's fortress. With the several parties thus situated the&#10;chase commenced.&#10;&#10;At the moment when the Hurons so suddenly changed their mode of attack&#10;their canoe was not in the best possible racing trim. There were but&#10;two paddles, and the third man so much extra and useless cargo. Then&#10;the difference in weight between the sisters and the other two men,&#10;more especially in vessels so extremely light, almost neutralized any&#10;difference that might proceed from the greater strength of the Hurons,&#10;and rendered the trial of speed far from being as unequal as it might&#10;seem. Judith did not commence her exertions until the near approach of&#10;the other canoe rendered the object of the movement certain, and then&#10;she" />
    <node id=" she thought of&#10;yielding, with the wish of being carried to the camp where she knew the&#10;Deerslayer to be a captive; but the considerations connected with the&#10;means she hoped to be able to employ in order to procure his release&#10;immediately interposed, in order to stimulate her to renewed exertions.&#10;Had there been any one there to note the progress of the two canoes, he&#10;would have seen that of Judith flying swiftly away from its pursuers,&#10;as the girl gave it freshly impelled speed, while her mind was thus&#10;dwelling on her own ardent and generous schemes. So material, indeed,&#10;was the difference in the rate of going between the two canoes for&#10;the next five minutes, that the Hurons began to be convinced all their&#10;powers must be exerted or they would suffer the disgrace of being&#10;baffled by women. Making a furious effort under the mortification of&#10;such a conviction, one of the strongest of their party broke his paddle&#10;at the very moment when he had taken it from the hand of a comrade to&#10;relieve him. This at once decided the matter, a canoe containing three&#10;men and having but one paddle being utterly unable to overtake fugitives&#10;" />
    <node id="Hist, a Native American woman and betrothed of Chingachgook, took several measures to convince Judith and Hetty to seek refuge in the Ark. She showed herself in the stern of the scow and made many gestures and signs, attempting to indicate that the girls should make a circuit to avoid the Castle and approach the Ark from the eastward. However, these signs were distrusted or misunderstood by Judith.&#10;&#10;There could be several reasons why Hist's signs were not trusted or understood. One possibility is that Judith was not yet sufficiently aware of the real state of things to put full confidence in either party, and therefore she may have been hesitant to follow Hist's directions. Additionally, it is mentioned that Judith kept more aloof and paddled slowly back to the north, where she could command the widest view and have the fairest field for flight before her. This suggests that Judith may have been prioritizing her own safety and desire for a clear escape route over Hist's instructions.&#10;&#10;Another possibility is that there was a language barrier or cultural misunderstanding at play. While Hist is a Native American woman, Judith and Hetty are European-American, and it's possible that they had difficulty understanding Hist's gestures or that there were cultural differences in communication styles. Ultimately, the reason for the misunderstanding is not explicitly stated in the narrative, but it is clear that Hist's attempts to communicate with Judith and Hetty were unsuccessful." />
    <node id="From the discovery of the moccasin on the shore, several deductions can be made: firstly, that someone had been near the castle, indicating possible recent human activity; secondly, given its pristine condition and location, it likely belonged to a Huron scout or assailant, suggesting the possibility of enemy presence in or around the castle; and thirdly, that they may not have been aware of the ambush laid by the Hurons near the castle.&#10;&#10;Despite the moccasin's discovery, Hutter and Hurry still proceeded towards the castle while conducting a deliberate survey of the building as they approached because they might have thought that the moccasin could have been left behind by someone unrelated to any potential danger at the castle. They might also have believed that they could handle any threat they encountered or that their weapons and skills would be sufficient for self-defense.&#10;&#10;Moreover, Hutter initially disagreed with Chingachgook's assessment of the signs of Huron presence near the old hut, indicating a degree of overconfidence in his own abilities to detect danger. It was only later when Hutter discovered the moccasin floating against the pile of the castle that he acknowledged the possibility of Huron presence near the old hut.&#10;&#10;Overall, while the discovery of the moccasin provided some evidence of potential danger, Hutter and Hurry still chose to proceed towards the castle, likely due to a combination of factors such as underestimation of the threat, confidence in their abilities, or the need to complete their mission." />
    <node id="The urgent circumstances that compelled Chingachgook to tell Hist to leave the Ark were the intense struggle between Hurry Harry and the three Hurons inside the castle. The combatants were caged, making it almost impossible for anyone to get in or out of the building. Chingachgook, who had all the arms in the Ark, felt at a loss because there was no means of using them or passing them to their owners. He wanted Hist to take the remaining canoe and join Hutter's daughters to save herself and warn them of their danger.&#10;&#10;However, Chingachgook was unable to convince Hist to leave the Ark despite her refusal due to the exigency of the moment, which did not allow for delay. Additionally, Hist, at that moment, could not be persuaded by any human power to quit the Ark, showing her firm determination to stay on board." />
