    <edge source="After the Hurons lost sight of Hurry's body, they realized that they had been shooting at the water instead of their target. They then aimed at his uncovered face, but by this time, Hist had begun pulling on the line, and the shots missed again, hitting the water near Hurry. Discovering their mistake, the Hurons tried to aim at Hurry's head as it emerged from the water, but he was already being dragged past the end of the scow and became concealed.&#10;&#10;Meanwhile, in the scow, the Delaware and Hist had hauled Hurry to their location, and Chingachgook severed the bark that bound his limbs using his knife. They then raised him high enough to reach the edge of the boat and helped him enter, as his arms were still nearly useless.&#10;&#10;As for the canoe of the girls, it was keeping a distance from the Ark, which had sailed and drifted quite half a mile away from the castle. The Delaware in the scow had lowered its sail, hoping to induce the sisters to seek refuge in the scow, but they continued to keep their distance. Hurry, now safe in the scow, called on Chingachgook to help take in the sail and secure the Ark." target="Hist, a woman in the narrative, took several desperate measures to save Hurry from drowning after he fell out of the scow. First, she opened the door at the very moment when the rifles were ringing, risking her own safety to intervene. Then, she stepped into the stem of the scow in time to witness Hurry's fall into the lake. Unconsciously placing her foot on the end of one of the sheets of the sail, she quickly gathered up all the spare rope and threw it in Hurry's direction with generous resolution, despite her awkwardness. This action enabled Hurry to secure himself and remain afloat until he was rescued by the Delaware and brought aboard the scow.">
